Quick Look at the Plots

Present-Value Relations (continued)

Question 1

1.Evaluate the long-term predictability of log dividend growth rates. In particular, compute overlapping long-term log dividend growth rates and regress them on appropriate information variables of your choice prevailing at the beginning of the corresponding period. What do you find?

I what follows I run the long-horizon regressions. To do so, I make use of four forecasting variables of my choice: price-dividend ratio, price-earnings ratio, log dividend-price ratio and the yield spread between long- and short-interest rates. I derive the latter measure from the dataset available at package . A common pattern that arises, at least in the first 3 panels, is the increase in predictive power and statistical significance as the holding period increases. This implies that these three variables, as of the beginning of the holding period, contain some information in encapsulated in long-run expectations.

In Panel B, we can also notice that the price-earnings ratio is little informative about cumulative the log dividend growth rate and, although not statistically signicantly, it is possibly negatively correlated with it. Quite to the contrary and not surprisingly, we can observe in Panel C that the log dividend-price ratio has largest R-sq (about 13 percent). In addition to this, there is also evidence of the hump-shaped response of the R-sq and t-statistic after quarter 48, after which both statistics decline for this variable. This hints in the direction for the dividend yield to be a quite good proxy for very long-run expectations concerning returns.

Lastly, the very measure of the the yield spread contains by construction scarce, if any, prdictive information concerning the medium run. This pattern is visible in Panel D, rightmost column, where the R-sq is basically zero, and the corresponding p-value is almost 1. However, the yield spread is a much better forecasting variable of the cumulative log dividend growth rate over the short and the long run.

Question 1

Analyze the short-run dynamics by estimating a VAR(1) model for logreturns,log dividend-price ratios, earnings-price ratios as well as log dividend growth rates based on the constructed price index. Estimate the individual equations separately and interpret the estimates. Moreover, compute the correlation matrix of the residual series based on all four equations. What can you learn from these correlations?

I estimate a VAR(1) equation-by-equation, compute forecast error variance decomposition for 2 quarters ahead by iterating forward the reduced-form VAR, and show the correlation matrix. I avoid to show the estimated coefficient because I argue that it is more instructive to look at the errror variance decomposition. The two quarters ahead are an arbitrary short run of my choice. I turn to the FEVD first.

Errors in forecasting log returns are not explained by shocks occurring to other variables, as most of the error news of the log returns themselves. A similar picture emerges the log dividend growth rate and the and the earnings-price ratio. On the contrary, already one quarter ahead, only 19 percen of unpredicted changes in the log dividend-price ratio can be attributed to its own shocks. More than 57 percent is indeed due to shocks to the log returns, and to a minor extent by news in the log dividend growth rate. This relationship exacerbtes in the second quarter forecasted error variance. Hence, there does not to be much interaction among these 4 variables if one excludes the string expectational relationship between log dividend yields and log returns.

Optimal Investment in Bonds

The Kelly Criterion

In this section I have fitted the yield curve using the Svensson-Siegel-Nelson using the US Treasury yields at weekly frequency. I subsequently proceed to compute the prices of 10 bonds that mature in 1,2,,10 years using the estimated spot rates. Lastly, I apply the Kelly criterion using Montecarlo simulations. One could, for example, allow \(c_{i}>1\) to include leverage, considerations and \(c_{i}< 0\) to model short sales. In these simulations, I allow for four scenarios.

  1. Short Sales not allowed, Leverage not allowed;

  2. Short Sales allowed, Leverage not allowed;

  3. Short Sales not allowed, Leverage allowed;

  4. Short Sales not allowed, Leverage allowed.

I impose a leverage constraint at 75%. A higher margin requirement would mean that less leverage can be taken. Throughout, I assume that all capital shall be invested, so that the sum of the weights is equal to 1.

I find that the highest median expected wealth level is achieved in a situation in which short sales are not allowed and leverage is allowed. However, we can also notice how actually the largest cumulative log wealth is achieved when short sales are allowed, but leverage is not.
